{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473517"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2480"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2480"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.76,0.11,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69960"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2823"},{"type":"tags","id":"3622"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of migratory joint pain. The pain began in his knees and has progressed to involve both elbows. He reports feeling feverish. He had an upper respiratory tract infection six weeks ago that resolved with supportive care. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not smoke, drink alcohol, or use recreational drugs. He has no tattoos and is not sexually active.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals normal first and second heart sounds with an early diastolic murmur maximal at the left sternal edge, third intercostal space. There is a faint pink macular rash with poorly defined borders over his torso and arms. Soft nodules are palpable around both elbows. Initial blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 135 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 7 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-10.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to assist with diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ECG","High-sensitivity troponin","Anti-streptolysin O titre","Blood culture","Throat swab for culture and sensitivity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Jones Criteria for diagnosing acute rheumatic fever include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvidence of preceding Group A Streptococcal infection PLUS\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo major criteria OR one major and two minor criteria\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMajor criteria: carditis, polyarthritis, chorea, erythema marginatum, subcutaneous nodules\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMinor criteria: fever, arthralgia, elevated inflammatory markers, prolonged PR interval on ECG\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of acute rheumatic fever, including migratory polyarthritis, fever, carditis (evidenced by the early diastolic murmur suggesting aortic regurgitation), subcutaneous nodules, and erythema marginatum following a recent upper respiratory tract infection. The diagnosis requires evidence of recent Group A Streptococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-streptolysin O titre\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation as it provides evidence of recent infection with \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, which is essential for diagnosing rheumatic fever according to the Jones Criteria. A rising or elevated titre supports the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThroat swab\u003C/strong\u003E for culture and sensitivity would be unlikely to yield Group A Streptococcus at this stage, as the preceding infection occurred six weeks ago. Serological evidence of recent infection would be more useful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E changes, particularly PR interval prolongation, can occur in rheumatic fever but are neither sensitive nor specific enough to confirm the diagnosis. They represent only a minor Jones criterion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-sensitivity troponin\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated if there is associated carditis but is not a diagnostic criterion for rheumatic fever and would not help establish the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood culture\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if infective endocarditis was suspected, but the clinical picture (migratory arthritis, erythema marginatum, subcutaneous nodules) is much more consistent with rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rheumatic fever commonly presents with migratory polyarthritis, fever, and carditis following a Group A Streptococcal infection.","Anti-streptolysin O titre is a key diagnostic test for confirming recent Streptococcal infection in suspected rheumatic fever.","The Jones Criteria, including evidence of preceding Streptococcal infection, are used to diagnose rheumatic fever."],"references":["Geerts I, De Vos N, Frans J, Mewis A. The clinical-diagnostic role of antistreptolysin O antibodies. Acta Clin Belg. 2011 Nov-Dec;66(6):410-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22338301/","Special Writing Group of the committee on Rheumatic Fever, Endocarditis, and Kawasaki Association. Guidelines for the diagnosis of rheumatic fever: Jones criteria, 1992 update. JAMA 1992; 268: 2069-2073. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1404745/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69960"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2480"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69960"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-17T13:03:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-17T13:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2480"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"